[[Image:Neonazi-skinheads-weiss-und-stolz.jpg|thumb|right|325px|Neo-Nazi skinhead in [[Germany]]]] {{Neo-fascism}} {{Antisemitism}} '''White power skinheads''' are members of a [[white supremacy|white supremacist]] and [[antisemitism|antisemitic]] offshoot of the [[skinhead]] [[subculture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adl.org/hate_symbols/music.asp|title=White Power Music|accessdate=2007-10-07|last=|first=|coauthors=|year=2005|work=|publisher=[[Anti-Defamation League]]|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011040036/http://www.adl.org/hate_symbols/music.asp|archivedate=2007-10-11|df=}}</ref><ref name="cbsnews.com">{{cite news| url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2007/02/06/national/main2440306.shtml | work=CBS News | title=Immigration Fueling White Supremacists | date=2007-02-06}}</ref><ref>[http://partners.nytimes.com/library/national/race/061388race-ra.html - New York Times - "Neo-Nazi Activity Is Arising Among U.S. Youth"]</ref><ref>[http://ngcblog.nationalgeographic.com/ngcblog/2007/11/profile_of_the_new_american_sk.html National Geographic - "Profile of the New American Skinheads"]</ref> Many of them are affiliated with [[white nationalism|white nationalist]] organizations.
In the [[United States]], the majority of white power skinhead groups are organized at either the state, county, city or neighborhood level. The [[Hammerskins|Hammerskin Nation]] (HSN) is one of the few exceptions, due to its international presence.<ref>[http://www.whiteprisongangs.info/2009/05/skinheads.html Encyclopedia of Gangs 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807091349/http://www.whiteprisongangs.info/2009/05/skinheads.html |date=2009-08-07 }}</ref>
==History== The original skinhead subculture started in the late 1960s and had heavy [[United Kingdom|British]] [[mod (subculture)|mod]] and [[Jamaica]]n [[rude boy]] influences — including an appreciation for the [[black music]] genres [[ska]], [[soul music]] and early [[reggae]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m2005/is_1_38/ai_n6234788/pg_1 | work=Journal of Social History | title=Subcultures, pop music and politics: skinheads and "Nazi rock" in England and Germany | first=Timothy S. | last=Brown | year=2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Old Skool Jim |first= |title=Trojan Skinhead Reggae Box Set liner notes |publisher=Trojan Records |date= |location=London |id=TJETD169}}</ref><ref name="Oi!"/><ref>[http://www.reggaereggaereggae.com/Special%20Articles.htm Special Articles<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081217000127/http://www.reggaereggaereggae.com/Special%20Articles.htm |date=2008-12-17 }}</ref> The identity of skinheads in the 1960s was neither based on [[white supremacy|white power]] nor [[neo-nazism]] or [[neo-fascism]], but some skinheads (including [[black people|black]] skinheads) had engaged in "[[Gay bashing|gay-bashing]]", "[[hippie]]-bashing" and/or "[[Paki (slur)|Paki-bashing]]" (violence against [[British Pakistanis|Pakistanis]] and other [[British Asian|Asian immigrants]]).<ref>[http://www.skinheadnation.co.uk/tilburyskinheads.htm Skinhead History - the Tilbury Trojan Skins<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20050929223759/http://www.trojanrecords.net/articles/monty2.htm Monty Q&A<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> This began after [[Enoch Powell]]'s inflammatory [[Rivers of Blood speech]] in 1968, which unleashed "Paki-bashing" violence, often referred to as "skinhead [[Terrorism|terror]]" in the media, with the "Paki-bashers" often simply called "skinheads".<ref name="Ashe">{{cite journal |last1=Ashe |first1=Stephen |last2=Virdee |first2=Satnam |last3=Brown |first3=Laurence |title=Striking back against racist violence in the East End of London, 1968–1970 |journal=[[Race & Class]] |date=2016 |volume=58 |issue=1 |pages=34–54 |doi=10.1177/0306396816642997 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5327924/ |issn=0306-3968}}</ref>
The original skinhead scene had mostly died out by 1972, but a late-1970s revival emerged partly as a backlash against the commercialization of [[punk rock]]. This revival coincided with the development of the [[Oi!]] [[music genre]].<ref name="Oi!">{{cite book |last=Marshall |first=George |title=Spirit of '69 - A Skinhead Bible |publisher=S.T. Publishing |year=1991 |location=Dunoon, Scotland |isbn=1-898927-10-3}}</ref><ref>[http://2-tone.info/ 2 Tone Records<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.skinheadnation.co.uk/skinheadclothing.htm skinhead clothing and skinhead fashion<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.garry-bushell.co.uk/oi/ www.garry-bushell.co.uk - Oi! – The Truth by Garry Bushell<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090830192607/http://www.garry-bushell.co.uk/oi/ |date=2009-08-30 }}</ref> The late-1970s skinhead revival in Britain included a sizable [[white nationalism|white nationalist]] faction, involving organizations such as the [[National Front (UK)|National Front]], [[British Movement]], [[Rock Against Communism]] and — in the late 1980s — [[Blood and Honour]]. Because of this, the mainstream media began to label the whole skinhead identity as neo-Nazi.
<!--Removed sentence about Chicago Area Skinheads as the referencing was affecting readability and neutrality. Please re-enter, if you can, with one or two citations--> The racist faction of the skinhead subculture eventually spread to [[North America]], [[Europe]] and other areas of the world. White power skinhead groups such as the [[Hammerskins]] emerged, and racist skinheads gained acceptance among other organized white power organizations such as the [[Creativity Movement|Church of the Creator]], [[White Aryan Resistance]] and the [[Ku Klux Klan]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=310 |title=Southern Poverty Law Center - Hammerskin Nation |access-date=2009-03-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091019195853/http://www.splcenter.org/intel/intelreport/article.jsp?aid=310 |archive-date=2009-10-19 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>Phyllis B. Gerstenfeld, Diana Ruth Grant, "Crimes of hate - Chapter: Target recruitment of Nazi Skinheads" - p. 217, 218.</ref><ref>Betty A. Dobratz, Stephanie L. Shanks-Meile, "The white separatist movement in the United States" - pp. 69, 70.</ref> In 1988, there were approximately 2,000 neo-Nazi skinheads in the United States.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://partners.nytimes.com/library/national/race/061388race-ra.html | work=The New York Times}}</ref>
In 1995, neo-Nazi skinheads Malcolm Wright Jr. and James N. Burmeister were charged with the murder of an [[African American]] couple in North Carolina.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/02/28/us/ex-gi-at-fort-bragg-is-convicted-in-killing-of-2-blacks.html|title= Ex-G.I. at Fort Bragg Is Convicted in Killing of 2 Blacks|publisher= nytimes.com|accessdate= 2 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/03/us/another-soldier-convicted-in-race-based-killings.html|title= Another Soldier Convicted in Race-Based Killings|publisher= nytimes.com|accessdate= 2 March 2015}}</ref> Wright and Burmeister were in the [[United States Army]], and part of Fort Bragg's [[82nd Airborne Division]]. Wright and Burmeister were both arrested at a trailer park where police found a 9-mm semiautomatic pistol, a Nazi flag, white supremacist pamphlets, and other gang paraphernalia. Both men were sentenced to life in prison.
[[Image:Neo-Nazi Skinhead.jpg|thumb|left|A neo-Nazi skinhead from Germany in front of a [[List of German flags#German Empire|Imperial-era Reichskriegsflagge]], a popular symbol for German neo-Nazis as a substitute for banned Nazi symbols]]
According to a 2007 report by the [[Anti-Defamation League]], groups such as white power skinheads, neo-Nazis, and the [[Ku Klux Klan]] have been growing more active in the United States, with a particular focus on [[Nativism (politics)|opposition to illegal immigration]].<ref name="cbsnews.com"/>
== Style and clothing == [[Skinhead]]s of all types are known for wearing [[Dr. Martens]] or [[Combat boot|combat-style boots]], [[flight jacket]]s, [[jeans]] and [[suspenders]] (also known as braces). Some white power skinheads wear badges, chains or rings featuring [[Nazism|Nazi]] or [[White supremacy|white power]] emblems.<ref>[http://www.splcenter.org/blog/2007/09/21/nyt-fashion-pub-skinhead-style-is-back/ Southern Poverty Law Center - "Skinhead Style is Back"]</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/magazine/6546617.stm BBC News - "Under the skin"]</ref> Many [[Punk fashion|punk]]-influenced [[Oi!]] skinheads dress similarly to white power skinheads, without the racist or neo-Nazi symbols.
In contrast to the 1960s-style [[Mod (subculture)|mod]]-influenced [[Trojan skinhead]]s, white power skinheads have typically worn higher boots, [[T-shirt]]s, [[flight jacket]]s and army [[trousers]] or [[jeans]] instead of [[Sta-Prest]] trousers or suits. Some white power or moderately right-wing/nationalist skinheads may dress quasi-traditional with Fred Perry or button down shirts and Harrington or [[denim jacket]]s. They usually crop their hair shorter than the 1960s-style skinheads — often to [[Buzz cut|grade 0]] length — or they shave their heads completely with a [[razor]]. White power skinheads tend to have more [[tattoo]]s than the skinheads of the 1960s, many of whom had no tattoos at all. These tattoos often feature Nazi, racist, or nationalistic imagery. Rune symbols as well as Nordic, Celtic and Germanic artwork are also common themes.
In [[Germany]], [[Spain]] and the [[Netherlands]], the [[Lonsdale (brand)|Lonsdale]] clothing brand has been popular among some [[Neo-Nazism|neo-Nazi]] skinheads. This was partly because the four middle letters of Lonsdale, ''NSDA'', are almost the same as the abbreviation for the name of [[Adolf Hitler]]'s political party, the [[Nazi Party|Nationalsozialistische Deutsche Arbeiterpartei]] (NSDAP).<ref>{{cite news | url=http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article352747.ece | work=The Independent | location=London | title=Lonsdale faces ban over 'neo-Nazi associations' | first=Tony | last=Paterson | date=2006-03-22 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080117155158/http://news.independent.co.uk/europe/article352747.ece | archivedate=2008-01-17 | df= }}</ref> The Lonsdale brand has been popular with non-racist skinheads for decades, and the company has sponsored [[Anti-racism|anti-racist]] events and campaigns, and has refused to deliver products to known neo-Nazi retailers.<ref>[http://www.dailynews.co.za/index.php?fArticleId=2401151 "Branded youths"]. ''Daily News''. 7 February 2005. Retrieved 2010-01-05.</ref>{{clear left}}
